v75: The Pareto-Lorenz a coefficients were computed using the top shares estimates (from the top 0.1% share within the top 1% share): a=1/[1-log(S1%/S0.1%)/log(10)].
v76: The inverted Pareto-Lorenz b coefficients were computed from the Pareto-Lorenz a coefficients using the formula b=a/(a-1). Alternatively they can be computed by using directly the top income shares estimates and the formula: b=1/[log(Skx%/Sx%)/log(k)].

v107: 1987-1995: based on the evolution of the tax value of single-family homes + agricultural properties (i.e., the 2 main categories of households' real estate). Before 1987: based on evolution of Olesen 2009 series. We checked that this gives results consistent with house price indices: housing slump from 1979 to 1982; then boom from 1982 to 1986; then slump from 1986 to 1995; then gradual increase through to 2004; then huge boom from mid-2004 to mid-2006 then slump.
